Comments:
This was not my first time participating in an exam with Wesley as a Chief/assistant chief, and I have significant concerns about the level of micromanagement. In this most recent experience, I was in a group of exceptional CFEs who have served as chiefs in various other exams, yet the level of oversight created an atmosphere that felt unnecessarily restrictive and, at times, uncomfortable.

I understand and appreciate Wesley's commitment to running a well-organized exam. However, the extent of micromanagement left many of us feeling undervalued and hindered rather than supported. A more balanced approach that allows experienced team members to contribute effectively would foster a more positive and collaborative environment.

As one of many who does these voluntarily, we dedicate our time to support these exams, but if this pattern continues, I fear it may discourage both myself and others from participating in the future.
Source_File: Feb-D33 New York University College of Dentistry.csv

Comments: This examiner was very unprepared with respect to the grading criteria and proper use of the grading tablet.  She had little understanding of the modification process even after all examiners were given additional instruction by me regarding the use of NAD and NAL in the course of their evaluations prior to the start of the exam on the second day of grading.  Even after I had personally counseled this examiner on three separate occasions regarding the necessity to clearly indicate her examiner number on modification request forms and progress sheets and to completely sign out on her tablet after concluding her grading session, she continued to fail to do this.  At one point her failure to do this properly resulted in a manikin remaining unnoticed in a chair for a lengthy period of time, and it was necessary for the candidate to be awarded 30 minutes of additional time.  At one point the examiner asked me to explain why she was getting more than one modification request from a candidate on a modification request sheet.  This candidate is clueless and a detriment to a successful exam.  I also expressed these concerns to my Assistant Chief who shared my sentiments.  He even asked if this was this examiner's first exam!  It clearly was not, as I have examined with her several times over the last couple years.
Source_File: Jan-D04 Class of 2025-Midwestern University College of Dental Medicine - Illinois.csv

Comments: This is NOT directed towards the Chief since he was only the messenger. This is a critique of the new policy which allows the Chief to extend time for candidates to complete procedures after the 3:00 finish time. In this case a candidate's took 4 hours to complete the Class III (which received a failing grade for caries remaining). The Class II preparation left the evaluation station at 2:50 p.m. as a failure for caries remaining. The candidate finished the restoration at 3:35. It failed for open contact. In the meantime, examiners had to stay; tear down was delayed; janitorial services were delayed (increasing costs to the school?) and to what end? The candidate failed three times over! We tout our exam as "fair". What is "fair" about allowing a candidate to take much more time when other candidates may have not done their best work because they were rushing? Please reevaluate this policy which serves no one and only makes us look weak.

Comments: Does not fully understand the role of the CFE . Allowed all candidates in his section to write both lesion diagnosis on the desk top cover instead of on the progress form (s) . When I brought it to his attention he was abrupt and dismissed it and stated it would be corrected. On second lesion check in for his section while he was at lunch the candidates second procedure was not filled in and they were getting it from the paper on their desk and one was asking.others .I quietly brought it to his attention again and he was unprofessional and angry. I tried to explain the importance/ reason and he was again unprofessional and walked off while saying I got it !! So I appropriately informed the captain and  AC so they could check the other candidates since he was so belligerent . He then came to me and said I had no need to tell so many people. I tried to explain the Chief would be able to check the other candidates sheets and to help explain why we share as a team to work together and improve he said I'm a volunteer and I said all of us on the team are and we assist each other. He said angrily " I'm done talking about it !" I said "then why did you come and talk to me about it again".The AChief said she discussed the process with him. The next morning I greeted him as all other team members . I do not think he should be a CFE or in any leadership position.

Comments:
Before we left the hotel she questioned how I became a member if I hadn't served on the Board of Dentistry. Later on we were all waiting in the kitchen and someone I knew walked in and I said hello. This person asked us all how long we were going to be there and I said " till we are done". Anne then blew up at me in front of the other examiners and would not let it go.
When I asked her to tell me what I did that was wrong so I could correct it, she got even louder and berated me in front of all the others without telling me what I did. I felt embarrassed and bullied by her. Later before we left she came up to me to ask if I was upset with her.
I told her she needed to tell me what was wrong when I asked her. I told her I was ok but really wasn't.  Anne then said we can't talk about the exam to anyone. I  did not discuss the exam, and was aware of that.
The next day another examiner called me to ask if I was ok and how she thought it was wrong the way I was treated and she hoped that would not discourage me from continuing. I thanked that examiner for calling.
Anne apparently let a voicemail yesterday for me to call her. I haven't returned the call as of yet because I was too hurt by her to do so. I felt devalued and bullied by this examiner.
She did allow me to observe her grading.
Source_File: Mar-DH01 Mott Community College.csv
